His doctrines then of body and void and the nature of atoms are certain truths which admit of but one explanation because every pheno- nemon here 011 6311311 attests them, and by most certain induction and reason they can be extended to the whole universe, alike to what is below and what is beyond our sense. Again it is a certain truth that the sun is really about the same size as it appears to us to be: see Epic. 1.1. 91, Lucr. v 564—591 : because from the experiments you can make with fire here on earth and the fact that so long as it is visible it does not diminish in size‚ but sooner indeed loses its brightness, you can by reason and induction apply these facts to the sun and the stars. Again that our world was formed nearly in the manner just described by Lucr. is true, because earth water air fire of which it is composed always do and must in like circumstances act in the way they are there represented as acting.
